### Is your feature request related to a problem? Please describe the problem.

I'm forced to use a backing field, rather than auto-properties, when I have a `required` field that should be set only by an internal method....maybe some code will help explain.

Given the following class, which is constructed by a static method:
```
public sealed class Artist : AggregateRoot<SubjectIdentifier>
{
    private Artist() { /* EF constructor */ }

    [SetsRequiredMembers]
    private Artist(SubjectIdentifier subjectIdentifier, EmailAddress email)
    {
        Id = subjectIdentifier;
        Email = email;
    }

    public required EmailAddress Email { get; init; }
```
because `EmailAddress` is `required` it cannot be `private set`, it must at least be `init`. This is not a problem, because the constructor is `private`.

However, I want to update this field, via a method internal to the class `Artist`. So, I'm forced to write:
```
    public required EmailAddress Email { get => email; init => email = value; }
    private EmailAddress email = null!;
```
which gives a code analysis warning, `S2292: Trivial properties should be auto-implemented`.

I can suppress this, but it's extra code and wouldn't it make sense that any `required` fields only require the same visibility as the most visible constructor?

### Describe the solution you'd like

Make any `required` fields only require the same visibility as the most visible constructor, i.e. in this case it would be `private set`.

